      <section id="market-research" class="section" data-reveal>
        <h2>🔎 Market research: beauty brand references</h2>
        <p class="muted">I reviewed booking and service experiences from beauty leaders (e.g., Bobbi Brown, Chanel, Sephora, Charlotte Tilbury, Benefit Brow Bar) to inform Watsons' direction.</p>
        <div class="grid two">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>UX considerations with brand signals</h3>
            <ul class="bullets">
              <li><strong>Personalization</strong> — Inspired by Bobbi Brown's 1:1 artistry and Chanel's beauty consultations: let users select preferred experts, service types, store, and time; save preferences and support a short pre‑visit questionnaire.</li>
              <li><strong>Service clarity</strong> — Like Sephora's clear service menu and Charlotte Tilbury's "quick pro" offerings: use simple categories, duration, price, and add‑on visibility so users know exactly what they're booking.</li>
              <li><strong>Seamless flow</strong> — Best‑in‑class flows minimize steps and uncertainty: keep the journey to 4–5 steps with a persistent progress bar, one confirmation screen, and timely reminders.</li>
              <li><strong>Value‑added services</strong> — Chanel and Charlotte Tilbury blend education and retail: integrate AR try‑on, tailored product recommendations, and post‑booking follow‑ups (care tips, reorder links, rebook).</li>
              <li><strong>Accessibility</strong> — Ensure inclusive sizing, color contrast, keyboard support, and descriptive labels; design for screen readers and reduced motion.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>UI considerations</h3>
            <ul class="bullets">
              <li><strong>Visual hierarchy</strong> — Borrowing from Chanel/Bobbi Brown: hero → categories → primary CTA; keep critical actions above the fold.</li>
              <li><strong>Brand consistency</strong> — Maintain Watsons' color, type, and tone across O+O, aligning app, web, and in‑store materials.</li>
              <li><strong>Theme choice</strong> — Light vs. dark changes mood; choose a palette that complements product imagery and improves readability.</li>
              <li><strong>Imagery & iconography</strong> — Use high‑quality, inclusive visuals and simple, universal icons to clarify steps and policies.</li>
              <li><strong>Mobile responsiveness</strong> — Optimize for touch: large targets, safe areas, sticky progress, and fast image loading.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="margin-top:16px;">
          <h3>Key takeaways for Watsons</h3>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>Prioritize a <strong>user‑centred, streamlined flow</strong> that makes availability trustworthy.</li>
            <li>Offer <strong>personalized and value‑added</strong> services (AR try‑on, tailored product sets, follow‑ups).</li>
            <li>Use a <strong>visually appealing, brand‑consistent</strong> interface with clear hierarchy.</li>
            <li>Ensure <strong>accessibility and mobile optimization</strong> from the outset.</li>
            <li>Leverage <strong>high‑quality imagery</strong> to inspire confidence and conversion.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      

